\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Physical substrate and the source of phantom load. (a)\nobreakspace  {}Vertical cross-section: chiplets sit on a silicon interposer that contains a small number of metal routing layers (typically 3--6 in current CoWoS); adjacent links are short horizontal wires while an express link is a longer wire that may traverse vias across layers. (b)\nobreakspace  {}Top-down view of a $4\times 4$ chiplet grid with only adjacent links: communication between corner chiplets S and D requires six hops, and every intermediate link must carry that transit traffic (phantom load). (c)\nobreakspace  {}Adding a single distance-3 express link (green) absorbs three of the intermediate hops in one physical wire, eliminating phantom load on those links. Our paper asks which non-adjacent pairs should receive such express wires under a fixed interposer routing budget.}}{4}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:interposer}{{2}{4}{Physical substrate and the source of phantom load. (a)~Vertical cross-section: chiplets sit on a silicon interposer that contains a small number of metal routing layers (typically 3--6 in current CoWoS); adjacent links are short horizontal wires while an express link is a longer wire that may traverse vias across layers. (b)~Top-down view of a $4\times 4$ chiplet grid with only adjacent links: communication between corner chiplets S and D requires six hops, and every intermediate link must carry that transit traffic (phantom load). (c)~Adding a single distance-3 express link (green) absorbs three of the intermediate hops in one physical wire, eliminating phantom load on those links. Our paper asks which non-adjacent pairs should receive such express wires under a fixed interposer routing budget}{figure.2}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Phantom load example on a 4$\times $4 chiplet grid. (a)\nobreakspace  {}Adjacent-only: C0$\to $C15 requires 6 hops via XY routing; every intermediate link carries transit traffic. (b)\nobreakspace  {}An express link C0$\to $C3 reduces the path to 4 hops, freeing 2 intermediate links.}}{4}{figure.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:phantom4x4}{{3}{4}{Phantom load example on a 4$\times $4 chiplet grid. (a)~Adjacent-only: C0$\to $C15 requires 6 hops via XY routing; every intermediate link carries transit traffic. (b)~An express link C0$\to $C3 reduces the path to 4 hops, freeing 2 intermediate links}{figure.3}{}}
